-1 ROLE PLAYING RP~
.

This is a basic guide as to how to role-play more efficiently. Phoenix
is a role-playing mud, so be prepared to role-play as much as possible.
There are several consequences for not role-playing. They can be
anything from just telling you, to a nochannel, to possible deletion
(this is very unlikely but you never know). So the overall theme of
this  is to role-play. Role-playing, or RP, can and does make mudding a
lot more fun. That is for you and others. One of the keys to
role-playing is to be consistent. Have a character and always play it
the same.
Remember, a character is just that, a character and not you. Try
different things. Don't let things on Phoenix or anything on the net
affect you off of the net. This is a screen with words no more. This is
your character on the computer and is make believe. Keep that in mind.
If someone kills you, is rude to you, or trashes anything about you,
remember this is your character, NOT you. React to it as your character
would.
The immortals will be watching and keeping tabs on the RP on Phoenix.
They or others will ask you questions about you and your life. All of
the thing that are stated in this file will be watched for.
To get into a character, or rather become that character, to ACT and
REACT as the person you have created is not as easy as it may sound. You
must think like the character. ACTING and REACTING are the keys to
role-play *period* If you can do that, the rest is a walk in the park.
To actually do that acting you need to suspend you (the person) from you
(the character). For instance, you may see someone getting insulted or
attacked. Now, you (the person) may want to see that person killed for
their crimes or insults,  you may resent them, possibly you will want to
interfere. But, if you (the character) is a blood-thirsty assassin or
reluctant to get into fights, then you would probably not interfere. You
may just cackle, grin, or laugh when things die.
The following is a list of the basics to help you create a character and
role-play that character:
1)  You must define your character so, create a history for that
character. The gods or other mortals may ask you for your background.
Come up with a land from which you came, a family history perhaps. How
did you receive your name? Why did you choose the profession you did?
The complex, detailed, and in depth a history the better. A history is
STRONGLY suggested.
2)  Keep in mind your race at all times when role-playing. Certain races
don't like magic or other races etc. For more information on how a
specific race is supposed to act and the like, read the help files for
that race or you can ask your local god.
3)  Keep in mind your class when you RP. This can affect a character
greatly. Read the help files for the classes or ask your local god for
more information.
4)  Don't forget to make a description for your character. This defines
a character extremely. This is also STRONGLY suggested.
5)  Don't make Out of Character comments over any channel except the
designated channels or possibly private channels.
  This means ANYTHING. From have a bad day to the score on a sports
event.
6)  A good addition to role-play is to act as if you were actually there
in the town. Use it's facilities. Go to the bar, the inn, or anything
anywhere in the Realms. Things like this, using your environment and
resources very helpful.
7)  A great thing for role-play are socials and emotes. Emotes more so
than socials because you can add your own quirks and personal spice.
   Examples of some role-playing emotes are:
a)  Puck grunts throatily.
b)  Puck burps loudly and disgustingly.
c)  Puck nods in recognition.
d)  Puck raises his ax high in the air and charges forward with fire in
his eyes!
8)  Along the same lines as the emotes, are to add quirks. Such as,
limps, accents, physical deformities, scars, and more.
  Examples:
a)  Puck limps toward you.
b)  Puck says," How are ye doin this day?"
c)  As Puck stretches his ax arm, a deep scar running the length of his
fore-arm festers and bleeds.
9)  Good RP includes a good name. To an extent, there is no limit to
names, as long as you can role-play it. Though some names will still
be restricted, just use common sense and no problems should arise. It is
suggested that you use FANTASY based names, and names that reflect your
character. Certain names go better with different races and classes. If
you need help or suggestions for names ask your gods.
10)  Anything can add to RP including your equipment. Sometimes it is
more advantageous to use equipment that reflects your character more
than just the best piece of eq. For example, a dwarven warrior, ;),
could wear the dwarven plate mail or mithril mail. An extremely good or
holy warrior might use Excalibur or a paladins sword. A vampire may
wear bloody cloaks.
11)  Remember all aspects of a character. From height, weight, and age
to your description, background, and habits. Everything is a factor.

A contest will be held occasionally for the best role-player. An award
will be given to the best role-player. Role-playing is difficult to be
taught in writing, so we will also guide you as time goes on. If you have
any questions about how to role-play, how to expand role-play, anything
about role-play, or anything else whatsoever, ask your role-playing
immortal.

 We are here to help you. If you need help in role-playing or anything
of the sort,  just speak up. Note the RP imm, talk to them, or talk to
any of the immortals. Role-playing is about acting, reacting, and most
importantly and to the point. Role-playing is about having fun.

LATE ADDITION: ROLEPLAYING IS COMPLETELY OPTIONIAL
~

